        overview_kicker: "Start here",
        overview_title: "Reading paths for first-time and advanced users",
        overview_lead: "This section starts with two things: which model/surface choices are current, and where first-time and professional users should begin. Today's edits are kept only in the Changelog near the bottom.",
        overview_update_1_title: "Key update dates corrected",
        overview_update_1_desc: "The July 20 run started by re-checking `codex/models` first and confirmed the recommended GPT-5.6 family remains `gpt-5.6-sol`, `gpt-5.6-terra`, and `gpt-5.6-luna`. Default Power uses Sol with medium reasoning; Max gives a single task more reasoning time, and Ultra coordinates subagents for large divisible tasks. If Ultra does not appear in the desktop app slider, enable Ultra in model picker slider under Settings > Configuration. GPT-5.5 remains previous-generation, while `gpt-5.2` and `gpt-5.3-codex` remain deprecated for ChatGPT-authenticated Codex. The use-case gallery still tracks 99 official individual cards after excluding collection pages.",
        overview_update_2_title: "Pricing and credits refreshed",
        overview_update_2_desc: "The guide keeps GPT-5.6 pricing scope split cleanly. Pricing lists GPT-5.6 Sol/Terra/Luna across Plus, Pro, Business, and API Key usage tables, while Fast mode is still documented for GPT-5.5/GPT-5.4 only. ChatGPT Work usage shares the same pricing, credits, and usage limits as Codex; API-key Codex uses standard API pricing instead of Fast mode credits.",
        overview_update_3_title: "Quickstart, IDE, and mobile path tightened",
        overview_update_3_desc: "The top path still keeps App-first onboarding separate from IDE/CLI + Docs MCP professional workflows, but the remote/mobile story was updated against today's official docs. The current docs say ChatGPT on iOS or Android can control an awake, online macOS or Windows Codex App host. The July 6 iOS changelog adds creating, searching, opening, forking, and managing Codex tasks from a conversation, staged/unstaged/branch/last-turn diff filters, selected transcript text insertion, SSH host shortcuts, and usage/credit details in the task menu. Remote access still uses the connected host's files, credentials, permissions, plugins, browser setup, Computer Use, and local tools.",
        overview_update_4_title: "Enterprise announcements separated",
        overview_update_4_desc: "The June 11 Codex app 26.609 release adds Plus/Pro rate-limit reset banking, Developer mode for Browser/CDP access, `/init` in the app composer, expanded Enterprise Computer Use, and per-app access controls for Computer Use on Windows. The June 18 Enterprise spend-controls announcement adds Global Admin Console credit usage analytics for ChatGPT and Codex, user/product/model breakdowns, unified Cost API access, and workspace/group/user spend limits, so the guide treats it as Enterprise admin operations. The June 24 AWS announcement is reflected only as an enterprise/provider deployment path for OpenAI models and Codex on Amazon Bedrock. Workspace Agents is separated as a ChatGPT Business/Enterprise/Edu/Teachers research-preview flow for shared cloud agents. The June 28 HP Frontier partnership is recorded only as enterprise adoption context.",
        overview_update_5_title: "Broader launch-post sweep",
        overview_update_5_desc: "I re-read `developers.openai.com/codex`, the Codex changelog, `developers.openai.com/blog`, `openai.com/index`, and `openai.com/codex` together. The July 9 GPT-5.6 and ChatGPT Work/Desktop items stay reflected as model and product context, and the CLI 0.144.6 GPT-5.6 bundled-instruction/context-window correction was added. The July 16 Wasmer and Cars24 stories are enterprise adoption context; the July 17 AI scorecard is an ROI measurement frame; the July 15 GPT-Red article remains prompt-injection safety research context.",
        overview_update_6_title: "Docs MCP, API changelog, and config rechecked",
        overview_update_6_desc: "Docs MCP, the config reference, and app/settings were rechecked around trusted project-scoped `.codex/config.toml`, the user-level requirement for machine-local provider/auth/profile/telemetry routing keys, shared CLI/IDE setup, the AGENTS.md steering snippet, `review_model`, `plan_mode_reasoning_effort`, granular approvals, `approvals_reviewer`, `default_permissions`, permissions profiles, app-level approval modes, sandboxed network proxy/requirements, keyring credential storage, forced login/workspace, `sqlite_home`, and hooks/plugin/skill controls. This run also clarifies that top-level `web_search` supports `disabled`, `cached`, `indexed`, and `live`, while `tools.web_search` can bound context size, allowed domains, and location. Sites remains split clearly: `.openai/hosting.json` stores project linkage and D1/R2 binding names, while runtime secrets are managed in the Sites panel.",
